Objective¶

This data set contains historical data of the customers who have taken loans from a German bank and the bank is facing issues with loan defaulters. The bank intends to build a machine learning model to predict whether the customer will default or not based on historical data

Data Dictionary¶

  • checking_balance - Amount of money available in account of customers
  • months_loan_duration - Duration since loan taken
  • credit_history - credit history of each customers
  • purpose - Purpose why loan has been taken
  • amount - Amount of loan taken
  • savings_balance - Balance in account
  • employment_duration - Duration of employment
  • percent_of_income - Percentage of monthly income
  • years_at_residence - Duration of current residence
  • age - Age of customer
  • other_credit - Any other credits taken
  • housing- Type of housing, rent or own
  • existing_loans_count - Existing count of loans
  • job - Job type
  • dependents - Any dependents on customer
  • phone - Having phone or not
  • default - Default status (Target column)

# Function to read the csv data and provide general information about the data.
def read_csv_file(path):
    df = pd.read_csv(path)
    # Prints the shape of the dataset
    print(f"\nThe shape of the dataset : {df.shape}")
    
    # Prints the number of null values in the each of the columns
    print(f"\nThe number of null values in the each of the columns : \n{df.isnull().sum()}")
    
    # Prints the total number of null values
    print(f"\nThe total number of null values in the dataset : {df.isnull().sum().sum()}")
    
    # Prints the total number of duplicate rows
    print(f"\nThe total number of duplicate rows : {df.duplicated().sum()}")
    
    return df

Findings :

  • checking_balance <0DM have more defaulters compared to other categories. So the customers who have less checking_balance tends to default.
  • credit_history doesn't give a good idea about the defaulters as the customers whose credit_history is good has more defaulters than the other categories.
  • purpose furniture/appliances have more defaulters.
  • employment_duration 1-4 years have more defaulters.
  • savings_balance <100DM have more defaulters.
  • Similary we can find which category have more defaulters and the bank can have a check before providing the loan.

test_size = .20 # set the test size (80:20)

X = df.drop(target_variable, axis = 1) # Features
y = df[[target_variable]] # Labels

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y,

# Create a general function to fit the models
def fit_model(**kwargs):
    name = kwargs['name']
    print(f"-------------Performing {name}-------------\n")
    print(f"-------------Started {name}-------------\n")
    model = kwargs['model']
    X,y = kwargs['X'],kwargs['y']
    fitted_model = model.fit(X,y)
    print(f"Model : {fitted_model}")
    print()
    print(f"-------------Completed {name}-------------\n")
    return fitted_model
In [31]:
# Create a function to plot the precision recall curve
def plot_precision_recall_curve(**kwargs):
    model = kwargs['model']
    X = kwargs['X']
    y = kwargs['y']
    y_scores_model = model.predict_proba(X) # predict_proba gives the probability of each observation belonging to each class
    precisions, recalls, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y, y_scores_model[:, 1])
    # Plot values of precisions, recalls, and thresholds
    plt.figure(figsize = (7, 7))
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], 'b--', label = 'precision')
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], 'g--', label = 'recall')
    plt.xlabel('Threshold')
    plt.legend(loc = 'upper left')
    plt.ylim([0, 1])
    plt.show()

# Create a function to get metrics for actual and predicted values
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = 'd')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
In [33]:
# Create a class to validate the model on training and testing data
class Evaluation:
    """
    This class performs the following operations on training and testing data -
    
        ----> Calculates accuracy, precision, recall, f1-score.
        ----> Prints classification report.
        ----> Prints confusion matrix.
        ----> Calculates Area under curve(AUC)
        ----> Prints the ROC curves
    """
    def __init__(self,**kwargs):
        # Assign the keyword arguments
        self.kwargs = kwargs
        self.model = kwargs['model']
        self.X_train, self.X_test = kwargs['X_train'],kwargs['X_test']
        self.y_train, self.y_test = kwargs['y_train'],kwargs['y_test']
        self.train_metrics,self.test_metrics = {},{}
        self.perform_model_prediction()
        self.accuracy_score()
        self.classification_report()
        self.confusion_matrix()
        self.roc_curve()

    def perform_model_prediction(self):
        # Get the predicted values by the model
        self.y_train_pred = self.model.predict(self.X_train)
        self.y_test_pred = self.model.predict(self.X_test)
        
        # Get the prediction probabilities by the model
        self.y_train_prob = self.model.predict_proba(self.X_train) 
        self.y_test_prob = self.model.predict_proba(self.X_test)
        
    def metrics(self,report):
        prec = round(report.loc["1"][0]*100,2)
        recall = round(report.loc["1"][1]*100,2)
        f1 = round(report.loc["1"][2]*100,2)
        return prec,recall,f1
    
    def accuracy_score(self):
        # Get the accuracy score for the model on training and testing data
        train_acc = round(accuracy_score(self.y_train,self.y_train_pred)*100,2)
        test_acc = round(accuracy_score(self.y_test,self.y_test_pred)*100,2)
        self.train_metrics['train_acc'] = train_acc
        self.test_metrics['test_acc'] = test_acc
        print(f"\nThe accuracy score for {self.model} model on training data is {train_acc}%")
        print(f"\nThe accuracy score for {self.model} model on testing data is {test_acc}%")
        
    
    def classification_report(self):
        # Get the classification report for the model on training and testing data
        self.train_report_df = pd.DataFrame(classification_report(self.y_train,self.y_train_pred,output_dict=True)).transpose()
        self.test_report_df = pd.DataFrame(classification_report(self.y_test,self.y_test_pred,output_dict=True)).transpose()
        self.train_report = classification_report(self.y_train,self.y_train_pred)
        self.test_report = classification_report(self.y_test,self.y_test_pred)
        print(f"\nThe classification report for {self.model} model on training data is \n\n{self.train_report}")
        print(f"\nThe classification report for {self.model} model on testing data is \n\n{self.test_report}")
        
        train_temp = self.metrics(self.train_report_df)
        test_temp = self.metrics(self.test_report_df)
        
        self.train_metrics['train_precision'], self.test_metrics['test_precision'] = train_temp[0],test_temp[0]
        self.train_metrics['train_recall'], self.test_metrics['test_recall'] = train_temp[1], test_temp[1]
        self.train_metrics['train_f1'], self.test_metrics['test_f1'] = train_temp[2], test_temp[2]
    
    def confusion_matrix(self):
        # Plot the confusion matrix for the model on training and testing data
        sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(self.y_train,self.y_train_pred) ,annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False)
        plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix for {self.model} model on training data')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
        plt.ylabel('Actual Label')
        plt.show()
        sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(self.y_test,self.y_test_pred) ,annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False)
        plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix for {self.model} model on testing data')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
        plt.ylabel('Actual Label')
        plt.show()
    
    def auc_score(self):
        # Get the AUC score for the model on training and testing data
        train_auc = round(roc_auc_score(self.y_train,self.y_train_prob[:,1])*100,2)
        test_auc = round(roc_auc_score(self.y_test,self.y_test_prob[:,1])*100,2)
        self.train_metrics['train_auc'] = train_auc
        self.test_metrics['test_auc'] = test_auc
    
    def plot_roc_curve(self,y_true,y_pred_prob):
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred_prob[:, 1])
        plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--')
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, marker='.')
        plt.xlabel("FPR(false positive rate)")
        plt.ylabel("TPR(true positive rate)")
        plt.show()
        
    def roc_curve(self):
        # Plot the ROC curve for the model on training and testing data
        self.auc_score()
        print(f"\nAUC for {self.model} model on training data is {self.train_metrics['train_auc']}")
        print("\nROC curve for training data: ")
        self.plot_roc_curve(self.y_train, self.y_train_prob)
        print(f"\nAUC for {self.model} model on testing data is {self.test_metrics['test_auc']}")
        print("\nROC curve for testing data: ")
        self.plot_roc_curve(self.y_test, self.y_test_prob)

Random Forest (Pruned)¶

  • Tuning the hyperparameters such as
    • n_estimators - The number of trees in the forest.
    • max_depth - The maximum depth of the tree.
    • min_samples_split - The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node
    • min_samples_leaf - The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node
    • max_features - The number of features to consider when looking for the best split
In [53]:

                            max_depth = 5,
                            min_samples_split = 5,
                            min_samples_leaf = 5,
                            random_state=0
                            )
                              
RF_pruned_model = fit_model(name = 'Random Forest',

Random Forest (Grid Search)¶

  • In order to improve the model performance we perform GridSearchCV
In [57]:
# Create a function to compare the current and best model till now
def current_vs_best_model(grid_search_models, X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test, name):
    if  f"{name}_best_model" not in grid_search_models.keys():
        print(f"Perfoming {name} first time.")
        grid_search_models[f'{name}_best_model'] = grid_search_models[f'{name}_current_model']
        best_train_score = grid_search_models[f'{name}_best_model'].score(X_train,y_train)
        best_test_score = grid_search_models[f'{name}_best_model'].score(X_test,y_test)
        print(f"\nBest Train score : {best_train_score}, Test score : {best_test_score}")
        
    else:
        curr_train_score = grid_search_models[f'{name}_current_model'].score(X_train,y_train)
        curr_test_score = grid_search_models[f'{name}_current_model'].score(X_test,y_test)
        best_train_score = grid_search_models[f'{name}_best_model'].score(X_train,y_train)
        best_test_score = grid_search_models[f'{name}_best_model'].score(X_test,y_test)
        print(f"\nBest Train score : {best_train_score}, Test score : {best_test_score}")
        print(f"\nCurrent Train score : {curr_train_score}, Test score : {curr_test_score}")
        if curr_test_score > best_test_score :
            print(f"\nThere is an improvement of {((curr_train_score-best_train_score)/(best_train_score))*100:.2f} % in training and {((curr_test_score-best_test_score)/(best_test_score))*100:.2f} % in testing datasets")
            grid_search_models[f'{name}_best_model'] = grid_search_models[f'{name}_current_model']
        else:
            print("\nNo improvement found in the scores!!")
    print(f"\nBest {name} model till now : {grid_search_models[f'{name}_best_model']}")
In [60]:
# Setting the parameters that needs to perform and performing K-fold cross validation (K=10)
rf_grid_params = {
    'n_estimators' : [100,200,300],
    'max_depth' : [4,6,8],
    'min_samples_split' : [3,5],
    #'min_samples_leaf' : [5],
    #'criterion' : ['gini'],
    'max_features' : [None],
}

RF_grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator= RandomForestClassifier(random_state=0),
                              param_grid=rf_grid_params,
                              cv=10) # 10-Fold Cross validation
name = 'RF'
selected_cols = important_cols[:6] # selecting the top 6 important columns
RF_grid_model = RF_grid_search.fit(X_train[selected_cols],y_train)

grid_search_models[f'{name}_current_model'] = RF_grid_model.best_estimator_

current_vs_best_model(grid_search_models, X_train[selected_cols],y_train,X_test[selected_cols],y_test, name = name)

# Setting the parameters that needs to perform and performing K-fold cross validation (K=10)
gb_grid_params = {
    'n_estimators' : [100,200],
    'max_depth' : [2,4],
    'min_samples_split' : [2],
    'min_samples_leaf' : [3,5],
    #'criterion' : ['gini'],
    'max_features' : ['sqrt'],
}

gb_grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator= GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=0),
                              param_grid=gb_grid_params,
                              cv=10) # 10-Fold Cross validation
name = 'GB'
selected_cols = important_cols[:6] # selecting the top 6 important columns
GB_grid_model = gb_grid_search.fit(X_train[selected_cols],y_train)

grid_search_models[f'{name}_current_model'] = gb_grid_search.best_estimator_

current_vs_best_model(grid_search_models, X_train[selected_cols],y_train,X_test[selected_cols],y_test, name = name)
